:INFO
Reading What Went Wrong From the Negative
Most C-41 problems are visible in the developed negative before you even scan. \
A properly developed negative has a warm orange-brown base, clear detail in \
shadows, and subtle gradation in highlights. Learning to read negatives directly \
on a light source will save you hours of scanning and post-processing guesswork.

:PATH
Negatives Are Too Dense (Overexposed Look)
Dense, dark negatives usually mean overdevelopment: temperature too high, time
|
:INFO
Negatives Are Too Dense (Overexposed Look)
Dense, dark negatives usually mean overdevelopment: temperature too high, time too long, \
or both. Verify your thermometer calibration against a known reference. If using a cheap \
dial thermometer, replace it. A 1 degree F error at 102 F causes visible

:PATH
Negatives Are Thin or Flat (Underexposed Look)
Thin, low-contrast negatives mean underdevelopment.
|
:INFO
Negatives Are Thin or Flat (Underexposed Look)
Thin, low-contrast negatives mean underdevelopment. Common causes: developer temperature \
too low, time too short, or diluted or exhausted developer. Mix fresh chemistry if your \
kit has been stored opened for more than 6 weeks. Use one-shot developer

:PATH
Magenta or Green Color Cast
A consistent magenta cast across the whole roll means developer was too cool.
|
:INFO
Magenta or Green Color Cast
A consistent magenta cast across the whole roll means developer was too cool. A green \
cast means developer was too warm. A cyan cast in shadows only often means the blix was \
too short and incomplete silver removal occurred. These casts can be partially

:PATH
Streaks or Uneven Development
Vertical streaks from the sprocket area mean insufficient agitation during the
|
:INFO
Streaks or Uneven Development
Vertical streaks from the sprocket area mean insufficient agitation during the first 30 \
seconds. Horizontal banding means agitation was too infrequent or done in a consistent \
pattern that created standing waves. Vary inversion direction slightly each

:NOTE
When to Trust the Process and When to Reshoot
A single bad roll is almost always equipment or temperature related, not a \
chemistry problem. Keep a log: date, chemistry batch number, temperature reading, \
and timing for every roll. After two or three rolls you will see whether a \
pattern is developing. If results are inconsistent roll to roll with the same \
chemistry batch, the thermometer is the first thing to replace.

:QUOTE
Every bad roll teaches you something a good roll never could. Run the failure \
back through the checklist before you blame the chemistry.

